mean_impute <- function(data)
{
  for (i in 1:length(data))
  {
    if(is.numeric(data[[i]]))
    {
      data[[i]] <- mean(data[[i]],na.rm=TRUE)  
    }
    
  }
  return(data)
  }

numeric_impute <- function(data)
{
  for (i in 1:length(data))
  {
    if(is.numeric(data[[i]]))
    {
      data[[i]]<-mean(data[[i]],na.rm=TRUE)
    }
    else
    {
      numeric_impute<-function(data)
      {
        for(i in 1:length(data))
        {
          data[[i]] <- mode_impute(data[[i]])
        }

  1. Write the following function. Give examples to test your function.

  • Input: a data frame

  • Output: Bar plots of all non-numeric variables

Hint: Similar function

bar_plot <- function(data)
{
  library(ggplot2)
  for (i in 1:length(data))
  {
    if (is.numeric(data[[i]]))
    {
      print(ggplot(data,aes(x = data[[1]]))+
      geom_bar(position = 'dodge')+
      labs(x = names(data)[1]))
    }
  }
}
bar_plot(df)

  1. Write the following function. Give examples to test your function.

  • Input: a data frame

  • Output: all possible the bar plots of a non-numeric variable filled by a non-numeric variable.

Hint: Similar function

bar_plot2 <- function(data)
{
  library(ggplot2)
  l <- length(data)
  for (i in 1:(l-1))
    for (j in (i+1):l)
  {
    if (is.numeric(data[[i]])& (!is.numeric(data[[j]])))
    {
      print(ggplot(data, aes(x = data[[i]], color = data[[j]]))+ 
              geom_bar()+labs(x = names(data)[i], color = names(data)[j]))
    }
  }
}
bar_plot2(df)
